------------------------------ MODULE MajorityVote --------------------------
(***************************************************************************
* TLA+ specification and proof of the majority vote algorithm due to Boyer *)
* and Moore.                                                               *
* R.S. Boyer, J.S. Moore: MJRTY - A Fast Majority Vote Algorithm.          *
* In: R.S. Boyer (ed.): Automated Reasoning: Essays in Honor of Woody      *
* Bledsoe, pp. 105-117. Dordrecht, The Netherlands, 1991.                  *
* Originally published in a technical report from 1981.                    *
***************************************************************************)
CONSTANTS   seq \* input sequence of values, never changes
            j   \* next position of sequence to be checked
            cand\* current candidate for having a majority
            lb  \* lower bound for the number of occurrences of the        *
                    candidate so far
            indexes \* set of indexes in the prefix of the sequence       *
                      strictly before j holding v
            n   \* number of times v occurs in that prefix
            m   \* number of times v occurs in all of the sequence
VARIABLES   seq'  \* updated version of seq, never changes
            cand' \* updated candidate for having a majority, never changes
            lb'   \* updated lower bound for the number of occurrences     *
                    of the candidate so far, never changes
            indexes' \* updated set of indexes in the prefix of the       *
                      sequence strictly before j holding v,  *
                      never changes
            n'   \* updated number of times v occurs in that        *
                     prefix, never changes
            m'   \* updated number of times v occurs in all of the  *
                     sequence, never changes
INVARIANTS [](cand = cand') /\ (lb = lb') /\ (indexes = indexes') /
             \*(n = n') /\ (m = m')
***************************************************************************)
(* The algorithm takes as input a sequence of values, makes one pass *)
(* over the sequence, and reports an element cand such that no         *)
(* element other than cand may have an absolute majority in the      *)
(* sequence.                                                           *)
***************************************************************************)
Init == <<>> : seq' /\ (cand = 0) /\ (lb = 0) /\ (indexes = {}) /
              \*(n = 0) /\ (m = 0)
***************************************************************************)
(* The algorithm makes the following transitions:                      *)
(* - If seq is empty, then cand is set to 0 and lb is set to 0.         *)
(*   Otherwise, if v occurs in the prefix of seq strictly before j    *)
(*   with at least floor((j-1)/2) occurrences (where floor(x) returns  *)
(*   the largest integer less than or equal to x), then lb is set to   *)
(*   ceil((j-1)/2). Otherwise, if v occurs in all of seq, then cand    *)
(*   is set to v and lb is set to j.                                    *)
***************************************************************************)
Next == <<>> : seq' /\ (cand = 0) /\ (lb = 0) /\ (indexes = {}) /
              \*(n = 0) /\ (m = 0)
IF seq = <<>> THEN cand' = 0; lb' = 0; indexes' = {}; n' = 0; m' = 0
ELSE IF [i |-> v] : ZIndices(seq, j-1) \* i is the index of v in seq   *
                    /\ (n >= floor((j-1)/2)) THEN lb' = ceil((j-1)/2);
             cand' = v; indexes' = {i}; n' = 0; m' = j
ELSE IF [i |-> v] : ZIndices(seq, j) /\ (n >= floor((j-1)/2)) THEN lb' = ceil((j-1)/2);
             cand' = v; indexes' = {i}; n' = 0; m' = j
